alone","Modified Medical Research Council scale alone","Body mass index alone","GOLD staging alone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EBODE index\u003C/strong\u003E is the most comprehensive and validated predictor of mortality in COPD. It incorporates multiple parameters that each independently influence survival:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBody mass index - nutritional status\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAirflow Obstruction (measured by \u003Cstrong\u003Eforced expiratory volume in one second\u003C/strong\u003E) - severity of airflow limitation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDyspnoea (measured by the \u003Cstrong\u003EModified Medical Research Council scale\u003C/strong\u003E) - symptom severity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExercise capacity (6-minute walk test) - functional status\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing single parameters alone is less reliable:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody mass index\u003C/strong\u003E only reflects nutritional status without capturing respiratory function or symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGOLD staging\u003C/strong\u003E only considers airflow limitation without addressing functional impact\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe BODE index\u0027s multi-dimensional approach provides superior mortality prediction because it captures both physiological and functional aspects of the disease. A higher BODE score (0-10) correlates with increased mortality risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The BODE index (Body mass index, airflow Obstruction, Dyspnoea, Exercise capacity) is a validated predictor of mortality in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.","Exercise capacity, measured by the 6-minute walk test, is a key component of COPD mortality prediction.","Multidimensional assessment tools are superior to single measures for predicting COPD outcomes."],"references":["Oga T, Nishimura K, Tsukino M, Sato S, Hajiro T. Analysis of the factors related to mortality in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease: role of exercise capacity and health status. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2003 Feb 15;167(4):544-9. doi: 10.1164/rccm.200206-583OC. Epub 2002 Nov 21. PMID: 12446268.","Phillips DB, James MD, O\u0027Donnell CD, Vincent SG, Webb KA, de-Torres JP, Neder JA, O\u0027Donnell DE. Physiological predictors of morbidity and mortality in COPD: the relative importance of reduced inspiratory capacity and inspiratory muscle strength. J Appl Physiol (1985). 2022 Sep 1;133(3):679-688. doi: 10.1152/japplphysiol.00352.2022. Epub 2022 Aug 11. PMID: 35952349.","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Li CL, Lin MH, Chen PS, Tsai YC, Shen LS, Kuo HC, Liu SF. Using the BODE Index and Comorbidities to Predict Health Utilization Resources in Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. Int J Chron Obstruct Pulmon Dis. 2020 Feb 19;15:389-395. doi: 10.2147/COPD.S234363. PMID: 32110007; PMCID: PMC7036670."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15478"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T22:18:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T22:19:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8169"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Re